  o1 = append (range (0, N), o2);
  print (o1);
@end smallexample

@fixme{Another subtly incorrect example.  The variable @code{v}
holds a vector boxed object as a tagged value, and is a root.}
@smallexample
  vector_set (v, i, cons_make (EOL, vector_ref (v, i)));
@end smallexample
@fixme{The apparently harmless call @code{vector_ref (v, i)} accesses
the vector @code{v} and returns its @code{i}-th element, without
performing any heap allocation; the problem is that the @emph{result}
of the function call is a heap object, which may be moved if
@code{cons_make} performs a collection; if the vector element
contained some pointer to an alive object, such as @code{v} itself,
that pointer would become invalid, and a root would be lost.  The
following variant is correct, with @code{tmp} being a root:}
@smallexample
  tmp = cons_make (EOL, vector_ref (v, i));
  vector_set (v, i, tmp);
@end smallexample
@fixme{As long as @code{cons} is defined correctly, which implies
temporarily registering both of its arguments as roots, there is no
need to use another variable for @code{vector_ref (v, i)}.}


