@node SH
@subsection SH
@cindex SH (architecture)
@cindex j-core
Minimal-threading is currently broken on SH, because of the architectural
limitation on instruction immediate width.  GCC solves the problem by using
PC-relative loads of constants close to the code directly in the @code{text}
section, a perfectly sensible strategy for ordinary C code which is unfortunately
incompatible with our relocated instruction intervals.  Sometimes GCC generates
PC-relative loads even for accessing constant bitmasks or @emph{offsets}
to be used for loading from the stack, when the constants are too wide to
fit in instruction immediates; such cases are unfortunately common in C
functions containing many automatic variables, or function calls.
@*
I need a workaround.

Of course direct threading relies on GNU C only, and therefore works
reliably on SH.

As a CPU with free-hardware implementations this architecture should
be high-priority.  Even if not the easiest ISA to support in Jitter I
find the SH an exceptionally beautiful minimalistic design, already
worth supporting on esthetic merit alone.

